    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you need to ask, then you need to explicitly initialize your fields/variables, because if you have to look it up, then chances are someone else needs to do that too.</p>\n\n<p>The value for a primitive <code>boolean</code> is false as can be seen <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/datatypes.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">here</a>.</p>\n\n<p>As mentioned by others the value for a <code>Boolean</code> will be null by default.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 29332,
      "reputation" : 12651,
      "user_id" : 79207,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 72,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/46336caa88972c4f2a00c254075e9ffe?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "planetjones",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/79207/planetjones"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 9,
    "last_activity_date" : 1307099373,
    "creation_date" : 1307099373,
    "answer_id" : 6226338,
    "question_id" : 6226290,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Boolean is an Object.  So if it's an instance variable it will be null.  If it's declared within a method you will have to initialize it, or there will be a compiler error.</p>\n\n<p>If you declare as a primitive i.e. boolean.  The value will be false by default if it's an instance variable (or class variable).  If it's declared within a method you will still have to initialize it to either true or false, or there will be a compiler error.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 326221,
      "reputation" : 4152,
      "user_id" : 647884,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49e9f25add9922c7f992be840bc3ada1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Bastardo",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/647884/bastardo"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 28,
    "last_activity_date" : 1530654017,
    "last_edit_date" : 1530654017,
    "creation_date" : 1307099398,
    "answer_id" : 6226341,
    "question_id" : 6226290,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>boolean</strong><br>\nCan be <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>.<br>\nDefault value is <code>false</code>.</p>\n\n<p>(Source: <a href=\"http://www.fluffycat.com/Java/Primitive-Variables/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Java Primitive Variables</a>)</p>\n\n<p><strong>Boolean</strong><br>\nCan be a <code>Boolean</code> object representing <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>, <em>or</em> can be <code>null</code>.<br>\nDefault value is <code>null</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2384381,
      "reputation" : 367,
      "user_id" : 2085658,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 33,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/EHI8F.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "snakedog",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2085658/snakedog"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1575725785,
    "creation_date" : 1575725785,
    "answer_id" : 59226529,
    "question_id" : 6226290,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<pre><code>class BooleanTester\n{\n    boolean primitive;\n    Boolean object;\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        BooleanTester booleanTester = new BooleanTester();\n        System.out.println(\"primitive: \" + booleanTester.getPrimitive());\n        System.out.println(\"object: \" + booleanTester.getObject());\n}\n\n    public boolean getPrimitive() {\n        return primitive;\n    }\n\n    public Boolean getObject() {\n        return object;\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>output: </p>\n\n<pre><code>primitive: false\nobject: null\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This seems obvious but I had a situation where Jackson, while serializing an object to JSON, was throwing an NPE after calling a getter, just like this one, that returns a primitive boolean which was not assigned. This led me to believe that Jackson was receiving a null and trying to call a method on it, hence the NPE. I was wrong.</p>\n\n<p>Moral of the story is that when Java allocates memory for a primitive, that memory has a value even if not initialized, which Java equates to false for a boolean. By contrast, when allocating memory for an uninitialized complex object like a Boolean, it allocates only space for a reference to that object, not the object itself - there is no object in memory to refer to - so resolving that reference results in null.</p>\n\n<p>I think that strictly speaking, \"defaults to false\" is a little off the mark. I think Java does not allocate the memory and assign it a value of false until it is explicitly set; I think Java allocates the memory and whatever value that memory happens to have is the same as the value of 'false'. But for practical purpose they are the same thing.</p>\n"
  } ],
